{"title_page": "Rudolf Steiner (footballer)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Other people||Rudolf Steiner (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Rudolf Steiner\n| fullname = \n| height = 1.70 m\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|df=yes|1937|4|7}}\n| birth_place= \n| death_date = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2015|12|3|1937|4|7}}<ref>{{Kicker}}</ref>\n| death_place = \n| position = [[Defender (football)|Defender]]\n| currentclub = \n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 1956\u20131960\n| years2 = 1960\u20131969\n| clubs1 = SC M\u00fcnchen von 1906\n| clubs2 = [[TSV 1860 M\u00fcnchen]]\n| caps1 = \n| caps2 = 176\n| goals1 = \n| goals2 = 5\n| nationalyears1 = 1964\n| nationalteam1 = [[Germany national football team|Germany]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 1\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n}}\n\n'''Rudolf Steiner''' (7 April 1937 \u2013 3 December 2015)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.dieblaue24.com/1860/8115-traurige-nachricht-meister-loewe-steiner-verstorben |title=\"Traurige Nachricht\": Meister-L\u00f6we Steiner verstorben |website=dieblaue24 |language=de |access-date=9 October 2017}}</ref> was a [[Germany|German]] football player. He spent 6 seasons in the [[Fu\u00dfball-Bundesliga|Bundesliga]] with [[TSV 1860 M\u00fcnchen]]. He represented [[Germany national football team|Germany]] once in a friendly against [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]].\n\n==Honours==\n* [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup]] finalist: 1965.\n* [[Fu\u00dfball-Bundesliga|Bundesliga]] champion: 1966.\n* Bundesliga runner-up: 1967.\n* [[DFB-Pokal]] winner: 1964.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Fussballdaten|steinerrudolf}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Steiner, Rudolf}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:German footballers]]\n[[Category:Germany international footballers]]\n[[Category:TSV 1860 Munich players]]\n[[Category:Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n\n\n{{germany-footy-defender-1930s-stub}}\n", "text_old": ":''for others with the same name, see [[Rudolf Steiner (disambiguation)]]\n\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Rudolf Steiner\n| fullname = \n| height = 1.70 m\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1937|4|7}}\n| birth_place= \n| death_date = December 2015 (age 78)\n| death_place = \n| position = [[Defender (football)|Defender]]\n| currentclub = \n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 1956\u20131960\n| years2 = 1960\u20131969\n| clubs1 = SC M\u00fcnchen von 1906\n| clubs2 = [[TSV 1860 M\u00fcnchen]]\n| caps1 = \n| caps2 = 176\n| goals1 = \n| goals2 = 5\n| nationalyears1 = 1964\n| nationalteam1 = [[Germany national football team|Germany]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 1\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n}}\n\n'''Rudolf Steiner''' (April 7, 1937 \u2013 December 2015<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.dieblaue24.com/1860/8115-traurige-nachricht-meister-loewe-steiner-verstorben |title=\"Traurige Nachricht\": Meister-L\u00f6we Steiner verstorben |website=dieblaue24 |language=de |access-date=2017-10-09}}</ref>) was a [[Germany|German]] football player. He spent 6 seasons in the [[Fu\u00dfball-Bundesliga|Bundesliga]] with [[TSV 1860 M\u00fcnchen]]. He represented [[Germany national football team|Germany]] once in a friendly against [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]].\n\n==Honours==\n* [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup]] finalist: 1965.\n* [[Fu\u00dfball-Bundesliga|Bundesliga]] champion: 1966.\n* Bundesliga runner-up: 1967.\n* [[DFB-Pokal]] winner: 1964.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Fussballdaten|steinerrudolf}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Steiner, Rudolf}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:German footballers]]\n[[Category:Germany international footballers]]\n[[Category:TSV 1860 Munich players]]\n[[Category:Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n\n\n{{germany-footy-defender-1930s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "S.A. Julio", "label": "safe", "comment": "ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rudolf_Steiner_(footballer)"}
{"title_page": "Georgia (typeface)", "text_new": "{{Infobox font\n| name = Georgia\n| image   = GeorgiaSpecimenAIB.svg\n| style   = [[Serif]]\n| classifications = [[Scotch Roman]],<br>[[Serif#Transitional|Transitional]],<br>[[Didone (typography)|Didone]]<br>[[PANOSE]]: 2263545234\n| creationdate = 1993\n| releasedate = 1996\n| creator = [[Matthew Carter]]\n| foundry = [[Microsoft Corporation]]\n| commissioned_by = \n| sample  =\n| latin = yes\n| greek = yes\n| cyrillic = yes\n| davanagari =\n| ipa =\n|}}\n'''Georgia''' is a [[serif]] [[typeface]] designed in 1993 by [[Matthew Carter]] and [[Font hinting|hinted]] by [[Thomas Rickner|Tom Rickner]] for the [[Microsoft|Microsoft Corporation]]. It was intended as a serif typeface that would appear elegant but legible printed small or on low-resolution screens. The typeface is inspired by [[Scotch Roman]] designs of the 19th century and was based on designs for a print typeface in the same style Carter was working on when contacted by Microsoft; this would be released under the name [[Miller (typeface)|Miller]] the following year.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Connare |first1=Vincent |title=Comments on Typophile thread... |url=http://typophile.com/node/75410 |website=Typophile}}</ref>  The typeface's name referred to a [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid]] headline \"Alien heads found in [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\".<ref>[http://web.nickshanks.com/typography/font-descriptions Typeface Descriptions & Histories]. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150424000832/http://web.nickshanks.com/typography/font-descriptions |date=April 24, 2015 }}.</ref>\n\n==Design==\nAs a transitional serif design, Georgia shows a number of traditional features of 'rational' serif typefaces from around the early 19th century, such as alternating thick and thin strokes, [[ball terminal]]s and a vertical axis. Speaking in 2013 about the development of Georgia and Miller, Carter said, \"I was familiar with Scotch romans, puzzled by the fact that they were once so popular...and then they disappeared completely.\"<ref name=\"Matthew Carter MyFonts interview\">{{cite web|last1=Middendorp|first1=Jan|title=Matthew Carter interview|url=http://www.myfonts.com/newsletters/cc/201310.html|website=MyFonts|publisher=Monotype|accessdate=11 July 2015}}</ref> Its figure (numeral) designs are lower-case or [[text figures]], designed to blend into continuous text; this was at the time a rare feature in computer fonts.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Daniels|first1=Simon|title=Forum thread|url=http://typophile.com/node/63979|website=Typophile|accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nCloser inspection, however, shows how Georgia was designed for clarity on a computer monitor even at small sizes.<ref name=\"Set on the Web-part 2\">{{cite web|last1=Yan|first1=Jack|authorlink1=Jack Yan|title=Set on the Web-part 2|url=http://jyanet.com/cap/0131fe2.htm|publisher=Jack Yan & Associates|accessdate=18 November 2017}}</ref> It features a large [[x-height]] (tall lower-case letters) and its thin strokes are thicker than would be common on a typeface designed for display use or the greater sharpness possible in print.<ref>[http://www.will-harris.com/verdana-georgia.htm \"Georgia & Verdana: Typefaces designed for the screen (finally)\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130828210842/http://www.will-harris.com/verdana-georgia.htm |date=2013-08-28 }}, by Daniel Will-Harris, accessed 24 November 2005</ref><ref>Friedl, Friedrich, Nicolaus Ott and Bernard Stein. ''Typography: An Encyclopedic Survey of Type Design and Techniques Throughout History.'' Black Dog & Leventhal: 1998. {{ISBN|1-57912-023-7}}.</ref> Its reduced contrast and thickened serifs make it somewhat resemble [[Clarendon (typeface)|Clarendon]] designs from the 19th century. \n\nGeorgia's bold is also unusually bold, almost black. Carter noted that, \"[[Verdana]] and Georgia...were all about binary [[bitmap]]s: every pixel was on or off, black or white...The bold versions of Verdana and Georgia are bolder than most bolds, because on the screen, at the time we were doing this in the mid-1990s, if the stem wanted to be thicker than one pixel, it could only go to two pixels. That is a bigger jump in weight than is conventional in print series.\"<ref name=\"Matthew Carter MyFonts interview\" /> Given these unusual design decisions, [[Matthew Butterick]], an expert on document design, recommended that organizations using Georgia for onscreen display license Miller to achieve a complementary, more balanced reading experience on paper.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Butterick|first1=Matthew|title=Miller|url=http://typographyforlawyers.com/miller.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150318145010/http://typographyforlawyers.com/miller.html|archive-date=March 18, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Miller|url=http://www.fontbureau.com/fonts/Miller/|publisher=Font Bureau|accessdate=11 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Georgia typeface is similar to [[Times New Roman]], another re-imagination of transitional serif designs, but as a design for screen display it has a larger x-height and fewer fine details. The ''[[The New York Times]]'' changed its standard font from Times New Roman to Georgia in 2007.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/ref/membercenter/help/OurRedesignfaq.html#h|title=What did you do to the font? FAQ|date=2007|website=[[New York Times]]}}</ref>\n\nGeorgia is a \"Scotch Roman\"&mdash;a style which originated in types sold by Scottish type foundries of Alexander Wilson and William Miller in the period of 1810&ndash;1820. According to [[Thomas Curson Hansard]], these were cut by London-based [[punchcutting|punchcutter]] [[Richard Austin (punchcutter)|Richard Austin]]. Hansard was writing within Austin's lifetime and this attribution is accepted by Austin's biographer Alastair Johnston, although historian [[James Mosley]] has expressed caution on the attribution.<ref name=type101>{{cite web|url=http://type101.fontbureau.com/new-faces-in-washington/|publisher=[[Font Bureau]]|title=New Faces in Washington|last=Lew|first=Kent|date=October 29, 2009|accessdate=January 22, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"James Mosley Scotch\">{{cite web|last1=Mosley|first1=James|authorlink1=James Mosley|title=Scotch Roman|url=http://typefoundry.blogspot.com/2007/02/scotch-roman.html|website=Type Foundry (blog)|accessdate=3 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Transitional Faces\">{{cite book|last1=Johnston|first1=Alastair|title=Transitional Faces: The Lives & Work of Richard Austin, type-cutter, and Richard Turner Austin, wood-engraver|date=2014|publisher=Poltroon Press|location=Berkeley|url=http://www.poltroonpress.com/book/transitional-faces-the-lives-work-of-richard-austin-type-cutter-and-richard-turner-austin-wood-engraver/|isbn=0918395321|accessdate=8 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Releases==\n[[File:Georgia cursived.svg|thumb|Georgia's [[italic type|italic]] uses a single-story 'g'.]]\nMicrosoft publicly released the initial version of the font on November 1, 1996, as part of the [[core fonts for the Web]] collection, and later bundled it with the [[Internet Explorer]] 4.0 supplemental font pack: these releases made it available for installation on both Windows and Macintosh computers. This made it a popular choice for web designers, as pages specifying Georgia as a font choice would display identically on both types if users installed the core fonts package (or later Internet Explorer), simplifying development and testing. Its creators also produced at the same time [[Verdana]], the first Microsoft sans serif screen font, for the same purposes. Some early public releases of Georgia included number designs between upper and lower-case, similar to those later released with Miller.<ref name=\"Georgia with lining numbers\">{{cite web|last1=Trenholm|first1=Sam|title=Georgia with lining numbers|url=http://samiam.org/blog/2014-06-21.html|accessdate=20 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Miller|url=http://www.fontbureau.com/fonts/Miller/styles/|website=Font Bureau|accessdate=12 May 2015}}</ref> Carter was asked by [[Robert Norton (typographer)|Robert Norton]], Microsoft's type director, to change these to text, a decision Carter later considered an improvement.<ref name=\"Quirky serifs aside, Georgia fonts win on Web\">{{cite web|last1=Rawsthorn|first1=Alice|title=Quirky serifs aside, Georgia fonts win on Web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/07/09/style/09iht-dlede10.2150992.html?pagewanted=all|website=New York Times|accessdate=20 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nNew versions of Georgia, along with its sister sans-serif font [[Verdana]], were released in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://georgiaverdana.com/|title=Introducing Georgia Pro and Verdana Pro|publisher=Font Bureau|accessdate=4 October 2013}}</ref> The extension of the original font, named Georgia Pro, features a set of additional typefaces and designs, including:\n*Additional weights, including condensed versions.\n*Specialized small caps designs.\n*Extensions to the character sets.\n*Extensions to the kerning.\n*OpenType typographic features such as [[typographic ligature|ligatures]].{{efn|Georgia's standard edition does include ligature designs, but they have to be inserted manually.}}\n*Lining figures\n\nThe expanded font was designed for organisations which had made extensive use of Georgia and Verdana due to its availability but desired additional versions for specific uses.\n\nMicrosoft has commissioned a number of variants. Georgia Ref, a variant of Georgia consisting of a single weight, but with extra characters, was bundled with Microsoft Bookshelf 2000, Encarta Encyclopedia Deluxe 99, Encarta Virtual Globe 99. MS Reference Serif, a derivative of Georgia Ref with a bold weight and italic, was also included in [[Microsoft Encarta]]. However, Microsoft's font manager Bill Hill wrote of it that \"I for one never felt totally comfortable with it as a book face. There's something very dark and 'vertical' about the way it feels\", and noted that Microsoft had commissioned an alternative, versions of the pre-existing typefaces Berling and [[Frutiger (typeface)|Frutiger]], for its [[Microsoft Reader]] [[e-book]] product.<ref name=\"Apple updates iBooks with new book fonts\">{{cite web|last1=Hill|first1=Bill|title=Apple updates iBooks with new book fonts|url=https://billhill49.wordpress.com/2011/12/09/apple-updates-ibooks-with-new-book-fonts|website=Bill Hill 49 (blog)|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref> Despite this, Georgia is used as one of the bundled book-reading fonts on several e-book applications.<ref name=\"Version 1.5 Improves Typography in iBooks on iPad and iPhone\">{{cite web|last1=Peters|first1=Yyves|title=Version 1.5 Improves Typography in iBooks on iPad and iPhone|url=http://fontfeed.com/archives/version-1-5-improves-typography-in-ibooks-onipad-and-iphone/|website=FontFeed|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nThe Cyrillic font won an award at Kyrillitsa in 1999.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120213181608/http://www.itcfonts.com/Ulc/2541/_sidebar1.htm U&lc Online Issue: 25.4.1: The Winners]</ref>\n\nMay 26, 2011 [[Matthew Carter]] received a [[National Design Awards#Recipients|Lifetime Achievement Award]] from the Smithsonian's Cooper-Hewitt [[National Design Museum]] in part for designing the Georgia font.\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[Core fonts for the Web]]\n*[[Segoe]]\n*[[Verdana]]\n\n==References and footnotes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n{{notelist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/typography/font-list/georgia Georgia font information] (Microsoft typography)\n*[https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/typography/font-list/georgia-pro Georgia Pro font information] (Microsoft typography)\n*[https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/typography/font-list/georgia-ref Georgia Ref font information] (Microsoft typography)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130828210842/http://www.will-harris.com/verdana-georgia.htm Article by Daniel Will-Harris]\n\n{{Microsoft Windows Typefaces}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Georgia (Typeface)}}\n[[Category:Transitional serif typefaces]]\n[[Category:Typefaces with text figures]]\n[[Category:Microsoft typefaces]]\n[[Category:Windows XP typefaces]]\n[[Category:Typefaces and fonts introduced in 1993]]\n[[Category:Typefaces designed by Matthew Carter]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox font\n| name = Georgia\n| image   = GeorgiaSpecimenAIB.svg\n| style   = [[Serif]]\n| classifications = [[Scotch Roman]],<br>[[Serif#Transitional|Transitional]],<br>[[Didone (typography)|Didone]]<br>[[PANOSE]]: 2263545234\n| creationdate = 1993\n| releasedate = 1996\n| creator = [[Matthew Carter]]\n| foundry = [[Microsoft Corporation]]\n| commissioned_by = \n| sample  =\n| latin = yes\n| greek = yes\n| cyrillic = yes\n| davanagari =\n| ipa =\n|}}\n'''Georgia''' is a [[serif]] [[typeface]] designed in 1993 by [[Matthew Carter]] and [[Font hinting|hinted]] by [[Thomas Rickner|Tom Rickner]] for the [[Microsoft|Microsoft Corporation]]. It was intended as a serif typeface that would appear elegant but legible printed small or on low-resolution screens. The typeface is inspired by [[Scotch Roman]] designs of the 19th century and was based on designs for a print typeface in the same style Carter was working on when contacted by Microsoft; this would be released under the name [[Miller (typeface)|Miller]] the following year.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Connare|first1=Vincent|title=Comments on Typophile thread...|url=http://typophile.com/node/75410|website=Typophile}}</ref>  The typeface's name referred to a [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid]] headline claiming \"Alien heads found in [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]].\"<ref>[http://web.nickshanks.com/typography/font-descriptions Typeface Descriptions & Histories] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150424000832/http://web.nickshanks.com/typography/font-descriptions |date=April 24, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==Design==\nAs a transitional serif design, Georgia shows a number of traditional features of 'rational' serif typefaces from around the early 19th century, such as alternating thick and thin strokes, [[ball terminal]]s and a vertical axis. Speaking in 2013 about the development of Georgia and Miller, Carter said, \"I was familiar with Scotch romans, puzzled by the fact that they were once so popular...and then they disappeared completely.\"<ref name=\"Matthew Carter MyFonts interview\">{{cite web|last1=Middendorp|first1=Jan|title=Matthew Carter interview|url=http://www.myfonts.com/newsletters/cc/201310.html|website=MyFonts|publisher=Monotype|accessdate=11 July 2015}}</ref> Its figure (numeral) designs are lower-case or [[text figures]], designed to blend into continuous text; this was at the time a rare feature in computer fonts.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Daniels|first1=Simon|title=Forum thread|url=http://typophile.com/node/63979|website=Typophile|accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nCloser inspection, however, shows how Georgia was designed for clarity on a computer monitor even at small sizes.<ref name=\"Set on the Web-part 2\">{{cite web|last1=Yan|first1=Jack|authorlink1=Jack Yan|title=Set on the Web-part 2|url=http://jyanet.com/cap/0131fe2.htm|publisher=Jack Yan & Associates|accessdate=18 November 2017}}</ref> It features a large [[x-height]] (tall lower-case letters) and its thin strokes are thicker than would be common on a typeface designed for display use or the greater sharpness possible in print.<ref>[http://www.will-harris.com/verdana-georgia.htm \"Georgia & Verdana: Typefaces designed for the screen (finally)\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130828210842/http://www.will-harris.com/verdana-georgia.htm |date=2013-08-28 }}, by Daniel Will-Harris, accessed 24 November 2005</ref><ref>Friedl, Friedrich, Nicolaus Ott and Bernard Stein. ''Typography: An Encyclopedic Survey of Type Design and Techniques Throughout History.'' Black Dog & Leventhal: 1998. {{ISBN|1-57912-023-7}}.</ref> Its reduced contrast and thickened serifs make it somewhat resemble [[Clarendon (typeface)|Clarendon]] designs from the 19th century. \n\nGeorgia's bold is also unusually bold, almost black. Carter noted that, \"[[Verdana]] and Georgia...were all about binary [[bitmap]]s: every pixel was on or off, black or white...The bold versions of Verdana and Georgia are bolder than most bolds, because on the screen, at the time we were doing this in the mid-1990s, if the stem wanted to be thicker than one pixel, it could only go to two pixels. That is a bigger jump in weight than is conventional in print series.\"<ref name=\"Matthew Carter MyFonts interview\" /> Given these unusual design decisions, [[Matthew Butterick]], an expert on document design, recommended that organizations using Georgia for onscreen display license Miller to achieve a complementary, more balanced reading experience on paper.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Butterick|first1=Matthew|title=Miller|url=http://typographyforlawyers.com/miller.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150318145010/http://typographyforlawyers.com/miller.html|archive-date=March 18, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Miller|url=http://www.fontbureau.com/fonts/Miller/|publisher=Font Bureau|accessdate=11 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Georgia typeface is similar to [[Times New Roman]], another re-imagination of transitional serif designs, but as a design for screen display it has a larger x-height and fewer fine details. The ''[[The New York Times]]'' changed its standard font from Times New Roman to Georgia in 2007.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/ref/membercenter/help/OurRedesignfaq.html#h|title=What did you do to the font? FAQ|date=2007|website=[[New York Times]]}}</ref>\n\nGeorgia is a \"Scotch Roman\"&mdash;a style which originated in types sold by Scottish type foundries of Alexander Wilson and William Miller in the period of 1810&ndash;1820. According to [[Thomas Curson Hansard]], these were cut by London-based [[punchcutting|punchcutter]] [[Richard Austin (punchcutter)|Richard Austin]]. Hansard was writing within Austin's lifetime and this attribution is accepted by Austin's biographer Alastair Johnston, although historian [[James Mosley]] has expressed caution on the attribution.<ref name=type101>{{cite web|url=http://type101.fontbureau.com/new-faces-in-washington/|publisher=[[Font Bureau]]|title=New Faces in Washington|last=Lew|first=Kent|date=October 29, 2009|accessdate=January 22, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"James Mosley Scotch\">{{cite web|last1=Mosley|first1=James|authorlink1=James Mosley|title=Scotch Roman|url=http://typefoundry.blogspot.com/2007/02/scotch-roman.html|website=Type Foundry (blog)|accessdate=3 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Transitional Faces\">{{cite book|last1=Johnston|first1=Alastair|title=Transitional Faces: The Lives & Work of Richard Austin, type-cutter, and Richard Turner Austin, wood-engraver|date=2014|publisher=Poltroon Press|location=Berkeley|url=http://www.poltroonpress.com/book/transitional-faces-the-lives-work-of-richard-austin-type-cutter-and-richard-turner-austin-wood-engraver/|isbn=0918395321|accessdate=8 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Releases==\n[[File:Georgia cursived.svg|thumb|Georgia's [[italic type|italic]] uses a single-story 'g'.]]\nMicrosoft publicly released the initial version of the font on November 1, 1996, as part of the [[core fonts for the Web]] collection, and later bundled it with the [[Internet Explorer]] 4.0 supplemental font pack: these releases made it available for installation on both Windows and Macintosh computers. This made it a popular choice for web designers, as pages specifying Georgia as a font choice would display identically on both types if users installed the core fonts package (or later Internet Explorer), simplifying development and testing. Its creators also produced at the same time [[Verdana]], the first Microsoft sans serif screen font, for the same purposes. Some early public releases of Georgia included number designs between upper and lower-case, similar to those later released with Miller.<ref name=\"Georgia with lining numbers\">{{cite web|last1=Trenholm|first1=Sam|title=Georgia with lining numbers|url=http://samiam.org/blog/2014-06-21.html|accessdate=20 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Miller|url=http://www.fontbureau.com/fonts/Miller/styles/|website=Font Bureau|accessdate=12 May 2015}}</ref> Carter was asked by [[Robert Norton (typographer)|Robert Norton]], Microsoft's type director, to change these to text, a decision Carter later considered an improvement.<ref name=\"Quirky serifs aside, Georgia fonts win on Web\">{{cite web|last1=Rawsthorn|first1=Alice|title=Quirky serifs aside, Georgia fonts win on Web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/07/09/style/09iht-dlede10.2150992.html?pagewanted=all|website=New York Times|accessdate=20 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nNew versions of Georgia, along with its sister sans-serif font [[Verdana]], were released in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://georgiaverdana.com/|title=Introducing Georgia Pro and Verdana Pro|publisher=Font Bureau|accessdate=4 October 2013}}</ref> The extension of the original font, named Georgia Pro, features a set of additional typefaces and designs, including:\n*Additional weights, including condensed versions.\n*Specialized small caps designs.\n*Extensions to the character sets.\n*Extensions to the kerning.\n*OpenType typographic features such as [[typographic ligature|ligatures]].{{efn|Georgia's standard edition does include ligature designs, but they have to be inserted manually.}}\n*Lining figures\n\nThe expanded font was designed for organisations which had made extensive use of Georgia and Verdana due to its availability but desired additional versions for specific uses.\n\nMicrosoft has commissioned a number of variants. Georgia Ref, a variant of Georgia consisting of a single weight, but with extra characters, was bundled with Microsoft Bookshelf 2000, Encarta Encyclopedia Deluxe 99, Encarta Virtual Globe 99. MS Reference Serif, a derivative of Georgia Ref with a bold weight and italic, was also included in [[Microsoft Encarta]]. However, Microsoft's font manager Bill Hill wrote of it that \"I for one never felt totally comfortable with it as a book face. There's something very dark and 'vertical' about the way it feels\", and noted that Microsoft had commissioned an alternative, versions of the pre-existing typefaces Berling and [[Frutiger (typeface)|Frutiger]], for its [[Microsoft Reader]] [[e-book]] product.<ref name=\"Apple updates iBooks with new book fonts\">{{cite web|last1=Hill|first1=Bill|title=Apple updates iBooks with new book fonts|url=https://billhill49.wordpress.com/2011/12/09/apple-updates-ibooks-with-new-book-fonts|website=Bill Hill 49 (blog)|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref> Despite this, Georgia is used as one of the bundled book-reading fonts on several e-book applications.<ref name=\"Version 1.5 Improves Typography in iBooks on iPad and iPhone\">{{cite web|last1=Peters|first1=Yyves|title=Version 1.5 Improves Typography in iBooks on iPad and iPhone|url=http://fontfeed.com/archives/version-1-5-improves-typography-in-ibooks-onipad-and-iphone/|website=FontFeed|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nThe Cyrillic font won an award at Kyrillitsa in 1999.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120213181608/http://www.itcfonts.com/Ulc/2541/_sidebar1.htm U&lc Online Issue: 25.4.1: The Winners]</ref>\n\nMay 26, 2011 [[Matthew Carter]] received a [[National Design Awards#Recipients|Lifetime Achievement Award]] from the Smithsonian's Cooper-Hewitt [[National Design Museum]] in part for designing the Georgia font.\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[Core fonts for the Web]]\n*[[Segoe]]\n*[[Verdana]]\n\n==References and footnotes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n{{notelist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/typography/font-list/georgia Georgia font information] (Microsoft typography)\n*[https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/typography/font-list/georgia-pro Georgia Pro font information] (Microsoft typography)\n*[https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/typography/font-list/georgia-ref Georgia Ref font information] (Microsoft typography)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130828210842/http://www.will-harris.com/verdana-georgia.htm Article by Daniel Will-Harris]\n\n{{Microsoft Windows Typefaces}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Georgia (Typeface)}}\n[[Category:Transitional serif typefaces]]\n[[Category:Typefaces with text figures]]\n[[Category:Microsoft typefaces]]\n[[Category:Windows XP typefaces]]\n[[Category:Typefaces and fonts introduced in 1993]]\n[[Category:Typefaces designed by Matthew Carter]]\n", "name_user": "Mikhail Ryazanov", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:punct., style", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Georgia_(typeface)"}
{"title_page": "Sagon Penn", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Notability|Biographies|date=April 2020}}\n{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n'''Sagon Penn''' (1962 - July 4 2002) was a martial arts expert<ref name=\"https://www.workers.org/2018/0...\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.workers.org/2018/08/38844/ |title=San Diego remembers Sagon Penn |last=Odom |first=M. Matsemela-Ali |last2=Muhammad |first2=Carl |date=2018-08-30 |website=Workers World |language=en-US |access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> and community leader from [[Southeast San Diego]] who worked as a karate teacher for children in the early 80's.<ref name=\"2002jul06\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sdut-sagon-penn-couldnt-have-life-2002jul06-story.html|title=Sagon Penn 'couldn't have a life'|date=2002-07-06|website=San Diego Union-Tribune|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Penn was subsequently acquitted for the 1985 controversial shooting death of a San Diego Police officer, the attempted murder of another officer and the attempted murder of a civilian ride along.<ref name=\"apnews\">{{Cite news|url=https://apnews.com/9038a9cef3aeee85a80597839e960620|title=Acquittal in Second Trial for Officer's Slaying|work=AP NEWS|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1987/07/17/Man-acquitted-in-racially-charged-cop-killing/7770553492800/|title=Man acquitted in racially charged cop killing|website=UPI|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref name=\"ODMP\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.odmp.org/officer/11276-agent-thomas-edward-riggs|title=Agent Thomas Edward Riggs|website=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>   \n\n== Multiple altercations and death of officer Riggs ==\nIn 1985 Penn's vehicle was pulled over in the [[Encanto, San Diego|Encanto area]] during a traffic stop by San Diego Police officers Thomas Riggs and Donovan Jacobs. Civilian police ride along Sara Pina-Ruiz was in the squad car when a physical altercation ensued resulting in Penn shooting and killing officer Thomas Riggs with his own service revolver, shooting and injuring civilian ride along Sara Pina-Ruiz and running over and injuring officer Donovan Jacobs with the police car as Penn, who was behind the wheel fled the scene.<ref name=\"apnews\" /><ref name=\"ODMP\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1987/07/17/Man-acquitted-in-racially-charged-cop-killing/7770553492800/|title=Man acquitted in racially charged cop killing|website=UPI|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Later that day Penn voluntarily surrendered himself to Police.\n\n== Trials ==\nRepresented by defense attorney Milton Silverman<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1986-03-02-me-1447-story.html|title=Penn Defense Could Rank With County's Most Costly|date=1986-03-02|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Penn was acquitted in 1986 on the more serious murder charge for killing officer Riggs and in a second trial in 1987 acquitted of all lesser charges. <ref name=\"apnews\" />\n\n== Community review board on police practices ==\nAfter the final verdicts, Superior Court Judge J. Morgan Lester gave unflinching criticism of the San Diego Police Department conduct in the case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1987-07-21-me-5199-story.html|title=Penn Trial Judge Assails Conduct of Police|date=1987-07-21|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> As a direct result of such criticism the Mayor and City Council at the time appointed citizens to a Citizens Advisory Board which ultimately led to the formation of the Community Review Board on Police Practices<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sandiego.gov/communityreviewboard/about|title=About the Board {{!}} Community Review Board on Police Practices {{!}} City of San Diego Official Website|website=www.sandiego.gov|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Death ==\nOn  July 4 2002,<ref name=\"https://www.workers.org/2018/0...\" /> Sagon Penn reportedly took his own life in what authorities determined was a suicide overdose.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sdut-sagon-penn-found-dead-apparent-suicide-2002jul05-story.html|title=Sagon Penn found dead in apparent suicide|date=2002-07-05|website=San Diego Union-Tribune|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Notability|Biographies|date=April 2020}}\n{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n'''Sagon Penn''' (1962 - July 4 2002) was a martial arts expert<ref name=\"https://www.workers.org/2018/0...\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.workers.org/2018/08/38844/ |title=San Diego remembers Sagon Penn |last=Odom |first=M. Matsemela-Ali |last2=Muhammad |first2=Carl |date=2018-08-30 |website=Workers World |language=en-US |access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> and community leader from [[Southeast San Diego]] who worked as a karate teacher for children in the early 80's.<ref name=\"2002jul06\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sdut-sagon-penn-couldnt-have-life-2002jul06-story.html|title=Sagon Penn 'couldn't have a life'|date=2002-07-06|website=San Diego Union-Tribune|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Penn was subsequently acquitted for the 1985 controversial shooting death of a San Diego Police officer, the attempted murder of another officer and the attempted murder of a civilian ride along.<ref name=\"apnews\">{{Cite news|url=https://apnews.com/9038a9cef3aeee85a80597839e960620|title=Acquittal in Second Trial for Officer's Slaying|work=AP NEWS|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1987/07/17/Man-acquitted-in-racially-charged-cop-killing/7770553492800/|title=Man acquitted in racially charged cop killing|website=UPI|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref name=\"ODMP\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.odmp.org/officer/11276-agent-thomas-edward-riggs|title=Agent Thomas Edward Riggs|website=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>   \n\n== Multiple altercations and death of officer ==\nIn 1985 Penn's vehicle was pulled over in the [[Encanto, San Diego|Encanto area]] during a traffic stop by San Diego Police officers Thomas Riggs and Donovan Jacobs. Civilian police ride along Sara Pina-Ruiz was in the squad car when a physical altercation ensued resulting in Penn shooting and killing officer Thomas Riggs with his own service revolver, shooting and injuring civilian ride along Sara Pina-Ruiz and running over and injuring officer Donovan Jacobs with the police car as Penn, who was behind the wheel fled the scene.<ref name=\"apnews\" /><ref name=\"ODMP\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1987/07/17/Man-acquitted-in-racially-charged-cop-killing/7770553492800/|title=Man acquitted in racially charged cop killing|website=UPI|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Later that day Penn voluntarily surrendered himself to Police.\n\n== Trials ==\nRepresented by defense attorney Milton Silverman<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1986-03-02-me-1447-story.html|title=Penn Defense Could Rank With County's Most Costly|date=1986-03-02|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Penn was acquitted in 1986 on the more serious murder charge for killing officer Riggs and in a second trial in 1987 acquitted of all lesser charges. <ref name=\"apnews\" />\n\n== Community review board on police practices ==\nAfter the final verdicts, Superior Court Judge J. Morgan Lester gave unflinching criticism of the San Diego Police Department conduct in the case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1987-07-21-me-5199-story.html|title=Penn Trial Judge Assails Conduct of Police|date=1987-07-21|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> As a direct result of such criticism the Mayor and City Council at the time appointed citizens to a Citizens Advisory Board which ultimately led to the formation of the Community Review Board on Police Practices<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sandiego.gov/communityreviewboard/about|title=About the Board {{!}} Community Review Board on Police Practices {{!}} City of San Diego Official Website|website=www.sandiego.gov|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Death ==\nOn  July 4 2002,<ref name=\"https://www.workers.org/2018/0...\" /> Sagon Penn reportedly took his own life in what authorities determined was a suicide overdose.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sdut-sagon-penn-found-dead-apparent-suicide-2002jul05-story.html|title=Sagon Penn found dead in apparent suicide|date=2002-07-05|website=San Diego Union-Tribune|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "name_user": "Spiritletters", "label": "safe", "comment": "title tweak", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sagon_Penn"}
{"title_page": "Antoine Joly", "text_new": "{{Infobox ambassador\n| name          = Antoine Joly\n| image         = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = [[16 July]] [[1955]]\n| birth_place   = [[Le Mans]]\n| ambassador_from = French\n| predecessor   = M. Michel Prom\n| country       = Suriname\n| term_start    = 17 January 2017 <ref name=\"appointment\" />\n| ambassador_from2 = French Guinea\n| country2      = CARICOM\n| term_start2   = 17 January 2017 <ref name=\"appointment\" />\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = [[France|French]]\n| party         = [[Rally for the Republic|RPR]]\n| other_names   = \n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Antoine Joly''' ([[Le Mans]], [[16 July]] [[1955]]) is a [[France|French]] politician and ambassador. From 28 March 1993 until 21 April 1997 <ref name=\"assemblee_nationale\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/histoire/trombinoscope/Vrepublique/Legis10/joly-antoine-16071955.asp|title=National Assembly Joly Antoine|access-date=7 April 2020|access-date=7 April 2020|website=Assembl\u00e9e Nationale}}</ref>, Joly was the deputy for [[Sarthe's 3rd constituency]] in the [[National_Assembly_(France)|National Assembly]]. His party affliation is [[Rally for the Republic|RPR]]. From 15 July 2011 until August 2015 he served as French ambassador to [[Nicaragua]].\n\nOn 17 January 2017 Joly was appointed as the French ambassador to [[Suriname]] as well the ambassador for [[French Guiana]] to the [[CARICOM]]. <ref name=\"appointment\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexte.do?cidTexte=JORFTEXT000033888850|title=Decree 16 January 2017 (in French)|access-date=6 April 2020|website=[[Journal Officiel de la R\u00e9publique Fran\u00e7aise]] }}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March 2020, Joly became the 8th victim of [[COVID-19]] in [[Suriname]]. <ref name=\"antoine_joly\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.dwtonline.com/laatste-nieuws/2020/03/25/franse-ambassadeur-in-isolatie-in-wanica-ziekenhuis/|title=French Ambassador in isolation in Wanica Hospital (in Dutch)|access-date=6 April 2020|website=De Ware Tijd}}</ref> He was first treated at the Wanica Hospital in [[Lelydorp]]. He was considered to be in reasonable condition, therefore he was transported to [[Cayenne]] in [[French Guiana]] on 29 March 2020, where he is quarantined. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ouest-france.fr/sante/virus/coronavirus/coronavirus-originaire-de-la-sarthe-l-ambassadeur-de-france-au-suriname-contamine-6795268|title=Original from Sarthe, the French ambassador to Suriname has been infected (in French)|access-date=6 April 2020|website=Ouest France}}</ref> On 7 April 2020 Joly recovered from Covid-19. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8oPhY-Kg81g|title=The French ambassador to Suriname, Joly Antoine - Guyana (youtube) (in French)|website=Guyane la 1\u00e8re via youtube|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Joly, Antoine}}\n{{France-politician-stub}}\n[[Category:Ambassadors of France]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox ambassador\n| name          = Antoine Joly\n| image         = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = [[16 July]] [[1955]]\n| birth_place   = [[Le Mans]]\n| ambassador_from = French\n| predecessor   = M. Michel Prom\n| country       = Suriname\n| term_start    = 17 January 2017 <ref name=\"appointment\" />\n| ambassador_from2 = French Guinea\n| country2      = CARICOM\n| term_start2   = 17 January 2017 <ref name=\"appointment\" />\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = [[France|French]]\n| party         = [[Rally for the Republic|RPR]]\n| other_names   = \n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Antoine Joly''' ([[Le Mans]], [[16 July]] [[1955]]) is a [[France|French]] politician and ambassador. From 28 March 1993 until 21 April 1997 <ref name=\"assemblee_nationale\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/histoire/trombinoscope/Vrepublique/Legis10/joly-antoine-16071955.asp|title=National Assembly Joly Antoine|access-date=7 April 2020|access-date=7 April 2020|website=Assembl\u00e9e Nationale}}</ref>, Joly was the deputy for [[Sarthe's 3rd constituency]] in the [[National_Assembly_(France)|National Assembly]]. His party affliation is [[Rally for the Republic|RPR]]. From 15 July 2011 until August 2015 he served as French ambassador to [[Nicaragua]].\n\nOn 17 January 2017 Joly was appointed as the French ambassador to [[Suriname]] as well the ambassador for [[French Guiana]] to the [[CARICOM]]. <ref name=\"appointment\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexte.do?cidTexte=JORFTEXT000033888850|title=Decree 16 January 2017 (in French)|access-date=6 April 2020|website=[[Journal Officiel de la R\u00e9publique Fran\u00e7aise]] }}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March 2020, Joly became the 8th victim of [[COVID-19]] in [[Suriname]]. <ref name=\"antoine_joly\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.dwtonline.com/laatste-nieuws/2020/03/25/franse-ambassadeur-in-isolatie-in-wanica-ziekenhuis/|title=French Ambassador in isolation in Wanica Hospital (in Dutch)|access-date=6 April 2020|website=De Ware Tijd}}</ref> He was first treated at the Wanica Hospital in [[Lelydorp]]. He was considered to be in reasonable condition, therefore he was transported to [[Cayenne]] in [[French Guiana]] on 29 March 2020, where he is quarantined. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ouest-france.fr/sante/virus/coronavirus/coronavirus-originaire-de-la-sarthe-l-ambassadeur-de-france-au-suriname-contamine-6795268|title=Original from Sarthe, the French ambassador to Suriname has been infected (in French)|access-date=6 April 2020|website=Ouest France}}</ref> On 7 April 2020 Joly recovered from Covid-19. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8oPhY-Kg81g|title=The French ambassador to Suriname, Joly Antoine - Guyana (youtube) (in French)|website=youtube|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Joly, Antoine}}\n{{France-politician-stub}}\n[[Category:Ambassadors of France]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n", "name_user": "KittenKlub", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antoine_Joly"}
{"title_page": "Preben Elkj\u00e6r", "text_new": "{{for|the Danish Olympic athlete|Preben Larsen (athlete)}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n | name = Preben Elkj\u00e6r\n | image = Preben Elkj\u00e6r.jpg\n | image_size = 220px\n | caption = Elkj\u00e6r in June 2011 in [[Viborg, Denmark|Viborg]] (photo Lars Schmidt)\n | fullname = Preben Elkj\u00e6r\n | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1957|9|11|df=y}}\n | birth_place = [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]\n | height = {{height|m=1.82}}\n | position = [[Forward (association football)#Striker|Striker]]\n | youthyears1 = 1963\u20131973 | youthclubs1 = Frederiksberg BK\n | youthyears2 = 1973\u20131974 | youthclubs2 = [[Kj\u00f8benhavns Boldklub|KB]]\n | youthyears3 = 1974\u20131975 | youthclubs3 = Frederiksberg BK\n | years1 = 1976 | clubs1 = [[Vanl\u00f8se IF|Vanl\u00f8se]] | caps1 = 15 | goals1 = 7\n | years2 = 1977\u20131978 | clubs2 = [[1. FC K\u00f6ln]] | caps2 = 9 | goals2 = 1\n | years3 = 1978\u20131984 | clubs3 = [[K.S.C. Lokeren Oost-Vlaanderen|Lokeren]] | caps3 = 190 | goals3 = 98\n | years4 = 1984\u20131988 | clubs4 = [[Hellas Verona F.C.|Verona]] | caps4 = 91 | goals4 = 32\n | years5 = 1988\u20131990 | clubs5 = [[Vejle BK|Vejle]] | caps5 = 39 | goals5 = 12\n | totalcaps = 333 | totalgoals = 143\n | nationalyears1 = 1975\u20131976 | nationalteam1 = [[Denmark national under-19 football team|Denmark U19]] | nationalcaps1 = 11 | nationalgoals1 = 6\n | nationalyears2 = 1976\u20131979 | nationalteam2 = [[Denmark national under-21 football team|Denmark U21]] | nationalcaps2 = 9 | nationalgoals2 = 9\n | nationalyears3 = 1977\u20131988<ref>{{cite web | url =http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/elkjaer-intlg.html | title = Preben Elkj\u00e6r-Larsen - Century of International Appearances | accessdate = 11 July 2012 | publisher = The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation}}</ref> | nationalteam3 = [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] | nationalcaps3 = 69 | nationalgoals3 = 38\n| manageryears1 = 1995\u20131996 | managerclubs1 = [[Silkeborg IF|Silkeborg]]\n}}\n'''Preben Elkj\u00e6r''' ({{IPA-da|\u02c8el\u02ccke\u02c0\u0250\u032f}}; born 11 September 1957) is a retired [[Denmark|Danish]] professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]].\n\nAmongst others, he played with [[Hellas Verona F.C.|Hellas Verona]] in [[Italy]], helping the club to the only major title of its history, the 1985 [[Serie A]]. Additionally, Elkj\u00e6r scored nearly 40 goals for the [[Denmark national football team|Danish national team]] in 11 years, being a leading figure for the Danish side under coach [[Sepp Piontek]] that played at the [[UEFA Euro 1984|Euro 1984]] and the [[1986 FIFA World Cup|1986 World Cup]] (a first-ever appearance), often hailed as the golden generation of [[Danish football]] by their countrymen. Elkj\u00e6r won the [[FIFA World Cup awards#Golden Ball|Bronze Ball]] award at the latter competition.  \n \nWidely regarded as one of the best forwards of the 1980s, Elkj\u00e6r finished second in the [[Ballon d'Or]] awards in 1985, having been placed third the previous year, and going on to finish fourth in [[1986 Ballon d'Or|1986]]. In [[Verona]] he is still remembered fondly, having earned the persisting nickname \"Il sindaco\" (the mayor) during his stint for the club. To this day, at least a few hundred voters in the city continue to write his name on their ballots at the mayoral elections.  Renowned for his goal-scoring abilities and persona, he also remains one of the most popular athletes in his native Denmark.\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Germany/Belgium===\nBorn September 11, 1957, in [[Copenhagen]], Elkj\u00e6r's career started with [[Vanl\u00f8se IF]] in 1976, where he stayed for just one season, playing 15 games and scoring seven goals. He then joined [[1. FC K\u00f6ln]] in [[Germany]], at the time one of [[Europe]]'s leading clubs. With the team, he won the 1978 [[DFB-Pokal|domestic Cup]] (his entire campaign consisted of nine minutes in the final, against [[Hertha BSC]]),<ref name=\"halloffame\">{{cite web | url = http://www.sportenshalloffame.dk/Default.aspx?ID=54 | title = Preben Elkj\u00e6r | publisher = SportensHallOfFame | language = Danish | accessdate = 17 April 2011}}</ref> but never got on with the manager or the harsh, disciplined atmosphere of a German dressing room,<ref>Lundberg (1988), p.91</ref> and eventually left. One falling out with the coach [[Hennes Weisweiler]] earned a legendary status in Denmark: Weisweiler approached Elkj\u00e6r and said that he had been informed that the player had spent the night at a nightclub in the company of a bottle of [[whiskey]] and a lady, and wanted to know if that was true. Elkj\u00e6r replied that it was a lie, in fact it was a bottle of [[vodka]] and ''two'' ladies.<ref name=\"Per H\u00f8yer Hansen: Det' H\u00f8yer\">Per H\u00f8yer Hansen: \"Det' H\u00f8yer\"</ref>\n\nIn February 1978, Elkj\u00e6r moved to [[K.S.C. Lokeren Oost-Vlaanderen]] in [[Belgium]] where he stayed for five years, the longest spell at any club during his entire career. There, he earned two nicknames: ''Chefen fra Lokeren'' (Lit: The Boss from Lokeren) and ''Den Gale Mand fra Lokeren'' (Lit: The Crazy Man from Lokeren),<ref name=\"Per H\u00f8yer Hansen: Det' H\u00f8yer\"/><ref name=\"DD\">{{cite news | author = Rob Smyth and Lars Eriksen | url = https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/oct/13/danish-dynamite-the-players | title = Danish Dynamite: The Players | work =[[The Guardian]] | date= 13 October 2009 | accessdate = 17 April 2011}}</ref> surpassing the 100-goal mark in official matches (98 in the [[Belgian First Division]] alone).\n\n===Verona===\nTwenty-seven-year-old Elkj\u00e6r signed for [[Hellas Verona F.C.]] in [[Italy]] in the summer of 1984 and, in [[1984\u201385 Serie A|his first season]] with the team, he played an instrumental role as it won the [[Serie A]] title, the ''[[List of Italian football champions|scudetto]]'', for the first time in its history; he aided to that conquest with a solo left-flank run against [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus FC]] (a 2\u20130 home win), where he lost his right boot, kept on running with the ball and ended up shooting home with his bootless right foot.<ref name=\"TheKnowledge\">{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/feb/08/theknowledge.sport | title = Socking it to the opposition | work = [[The Guardian]] | date = 8 February 2006 | accessdate = 17 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1984, Elkj\u00e6r finished third and in 1985 second in the [[Ballon d'Or|European Footballer of the Year]] awards, both times surpassed by [[Michel Platini]], who played for Juventus.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/europa-poy.html | title = European Footballer of the Year (\"Ballon d'Or\") | publisher= [[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] | accessdate = 17 April 2011}}</ref> During his four-year spell at Verona, he never scored ten league goals in a season, but never netted fewer than seven goals, for a total of 48 official ones.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.prebenelkjaer.com/carriera.php | title = Verona career | work = Official website | accessdate = 17 April 2011 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110715111748/http://www.prebenelkjaer.com/carriera.php | archivedate = 15 July 2011 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Return to Denmark/Retirement===\nIn 1988, Elkj\u00e6r made a comeback in Danish football with [[Vejle BK]].<ref name=\"halloffame\"/> He came to the club as the biggest star in the country, and attracted great crowds to the club's matches.<ref name=\"halloffame\"/> Aged already 31, he suffered a number of injuries while at Vejle,<ref name=\"halloffame\"/> and had a hard time living up to the high expectations of the crowds, eventually retiring two years later, having only appeared a total of 26 matches combined.\n\n==International career==\nWhile playing youth football for Frederiksberg Boldklub, Elkj\u00e6r made his debut for the Danish under-19 national team, in October 1975. He played a total 11 games and scored six goals for the under-19 national team, including three in three games at the 1975 [[UEFA European Under-19 Football Championship]].<ref name=\"Allekampe\">{{cite web | url = http://www.dbu.dk/landshold/landsholdsdatabasen/PlayerInfo/3708&allmatch=1#match | title = Preben Elkj\u00e6r \u2013 Alle hold (Alle kampe) | publisher =  DBU | language = Danish | accessdate = 17 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nElkj\u00e6r made his debut for the [[Denmark national under-21 football team|under-21s]] in June 1976,<ref name=\"Allekampe\"/> scoring nine times in as many games; this included three goals in the quarter-finals of the [[1978 UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship#Knockout stage|1978 European Under-21 Championship]] against [[Bulgaria national under-21 football team|Bulgaria]], though Denmark were eliminated on the [[away goals rule]].<ref name=\"Allekampe\"/>\n\nOn 22 June 1977, aged 19 years and 284 days, Elkj\u00e6r made his debut for the [[Denmark national football team|senior national team]], scoring both goals in a 2\u20131 win against [[Finland national football team|Finland]]. He played a prominent role in [[UEFA Euro 1984]], scoring two goals in four games,<ref name=\"Allekampe\"/> which helped pave the way for his move to Italian football.<ref>Lundberg (1988), p.136</ref> During the tournament, Denmark played attractive attacking football, but went out at the semi-final stage, losing to [[Spain national football team|Spain]] on [[Penalty shootout (association football)|penalties]].<ref name=\"Allekampe\"/> Elkj\u00e6r missed Denmark's last [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]] attempt, sending the ball high over the goal.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.dbu.dk/landshold/landsholdsdatabasen/LBaseMatchInfo.aspx?matchid=441 | title = Danmark \u2013 Spanien 1\u20131 | publisher = DBU | language = Danish | accessdate = 17 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nElkj\u00e6r also represented Denmark at the [[1986 FIFA World Cup]] as Denmark had qualified for [[FIFA World Cup|that competition]] for the first time, eventually progressing from the group stage as winners, only to be once again knocked out by Spain.<ref name=\"Allekampe\"/> During the tournament, he scored four goals, including a [[hat-trick]] against [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]],<ref name=\"Allekampe\"/> being named the most dynamic and powerful striker of the tournament,<ref name=\"FIFAp208\"/> and winning the [[FIFA World Cup awards#Golden Ball|Bronze Ball]] award as the third best player.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/fifa-gb86.html | title = FIFA Awards \u2013 World Cup 1986 \"Golden Ball\" | publisher = [[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] | accessdate = 17 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[UEFA Euro 1988|Euro 1988]] was Elkj\u00e6r's last tournament participation for him. On 14 June 1988, he played the last game for his country, aged 30 years and 277 days, as Denmark lost 0\u20132 to [[Germany national football team|West Germany]], finishing with three group stage defeats. In total, he played 69 international games, and scored 38 goals.<ref name=\"Allekampe\"/>\n\n==Playing style==\nElkj\u00e6r is regarded as one of Denmark's all-time greatest [[Forward (association football)|forwards]]. A notorious [[Tobacco smoking|smoker]],<ref name=\"DD\"/> his playing style was however not short of breath, being dominated by a rock-like determination.<ref name=\"DD\"/> He never seemed to give up on a lost ball \u2013 from time to time resulting in a goal.\n\nHis style was an unorthodox combination of physical confrontations<ref>Lundberg (1988), p.109</ref> and great [[dribbling]] abilities.<ref name=\"DD\"/> Described as \"powerful and dynamic\", Elkj\u00e6r could hardly be stopped when going on his own,<ref name=\"FIFAp208\">{{cite web | url = https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/afdeveloping/technicaldevp/50/09/00/fwc_mexico_1986_en_part4_279.pdf | title = FIFA World Cup \u2013 Mexico '86 \u2013 Official Report, p.208| publisher = [[FIFA]] | accessdate = 17 April 2011}}</ref> one of his trademarks. His aggression was matched by few,<ref name=\"halloffame\"/> and whenever he would receive the ball with his back to the goal he would immediately turn with the ball and attempt to head for goal.\n\nElkj\u00e6r's aggressive style of play was well combined with the calmness and vision of the younger [[Michael Laudrup]] when they played side by side on the national team,<ref name=\"FIFAp208\"/> and they were named the \"most effective\" attacking duo of the 1986 World Cup.<ref name=\"FIFAp208\"/>\n\n==Retirement==\nAfter his retirement from playing, Elkj\u00e6r took on the job as head coach of [[Silkeborg IF]] in the ''[[Danish Superliga]]'' in 1995.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.silkeborgif.com/historie.aspx | title = Historie | trans-title = History | publisher = Silkeborg | language = Danish | accessdate = 17 April 2011 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090131012258/http://silkeborgif.com/historie.aspx | archivedate = 31 January 2009 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> \n \nIn December 1996, he left the club to head TV sports channel ''TVS'', a newly formed corporation between national TV stations [[Danmarks Radio|DR]] and [[TV 2 (Denmark)|TV2]], the [[Danish Football Association]] and telecompany [[TDC A/S|Tele Danmark]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.danske-nyheder.dk/arkiv/1996.11.19.html#Elkj\u00e6r_TV-direkt\u00f8r | publisher = Danske-Nyheder.dk | title = Danish news on TVS from 19/11-1996 | language = Danish | accessdate = 17 April 2011}}</ref> The station was not a success, and was closed within a year of its opening.\n\nAdditionally, he worked as a [[UEFA Champions League]] [[Pundit (expert)|pundit]] at Danish [[Viasat|TV3+]], alongside [[Brian Laudrup]] and host Peter Gr\u00f8nborg.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.berlingske.dk/samfund/preben-elkjaer-om-nye-tv-tider-i-champions-league-nu-bliver-det-endnu-sjovere | publisher = Berlingske | title = Preben Elkj\u00e6r om nye TV-tider i Champions League: \u00bbNu bliver det endnu sjovere\u00ab | language = Danish | accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref>\n. In October 2019 he had an operation to remove a gallstone in Belgium.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bt.dk/fodbold/preben-elkjaer-hasteopereret-for-galdesten | publisher = BT | title = Preben Elkj\u00e6r hasteopereret for galdesten | language = Danish | accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Club===\n;[[1. FC K\u00f6ln]]\n*[[Bundesliga]]: [[1977\u201378 Bundesliga|1977\u201378]]\n*[[DFB-Pokal]]: [[1976\u201377 DFB-Pokal|1976\u201377]], [[1977\u201378 DFB-Pokal|1977\u201378]]\n\n;[[Hellas Verona F.C.|Verona F.C.]]\n*[[Serie A]]: [[1984\u201385 Serie A|1984\u201385]]\n\n===Individual===\n*[[Danish Football Player of the Year|Danish Player of the Year]]: 1984\n*[[Ballon d'Or (1956\u20132009)|Ballon d'Or]] \u2013 Third Place: 1984<ref>{{citeweb|url= http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/europa-poy84.html|title=European Footballer of the Year (\"Ballon d'Or\") 1984|work=RSSSF|accessdate=14 April 2015 }}</ref>\n*[[Ballon d'Or (1956\u20132009)|Ballon d'Or]] \u2013 Runner-up: 1985<ref>{{citeweb|url= http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/europa-poy85.html|title=European Footballer of the Year (\"Ballon d'Or\") 1985|work=RSSSF|accessdate=14 April 2015 }}</ref>\n*[[Onze d'Or|Onze de Bronze]] : [[Onze d'Or|1984]]\n*[[Onze d'Or|Onze d'Argent]] : [[Onze d'Or|1985]]\n*[[FIFA World Cup awards#Golden Ball|FIFA World Cup Bronze Ball]]: 1986\n*[[FIFA World Cup awards#All-Star Team|FIFA World Cup All-Star Team]]: 1986\n*[[Denmark national football team#Hall of Fame|Danish Football Hall of Fame]]\n*[[World Soccer Magazine|World Soccer The Greatest Players of the 20th century]]: The 100 Greatest Footballers of All Time<ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/best-x-players-of-y.html#ws100 World Soccer: The 100 Greatest Footballers of All Time] Retrieved 30 December 2015</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n===Footnotes===\n*{{cite book |title=Dansk Fodbold |last=Lundberg |first=Knud |authorlink= Knud Lundberg|volume=3. Gennembrudet til verdensklasse |coauthors= |year=1988 |publisher=Rhodos |location=Copenhagen |isbn=87-7245-260-9 |page= |pages= |url= |accessdate=}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Preben Elkj\u00e6r}}\n* [http://www.dbu.dk/landshold/landsholdsdatabasen/PlayerInfo/3708 National team data] {{in lang|da}}\n* [http://www.vejle-boldklub.dk/index.php?gammel_spillere=6406 Vejle Boldklub profile] {{in lang|da}}\n* {{Fussballdaten|elkjaerlarsenpreben|Preben Elkj\u00e6r Larsen}}\n* {{NFT player|pid=19458}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.prebenelkjaer.com/}}\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title=Awards\n|bg=Gold\n|bordercolor=Black\n|fg=Black\n|list1=\n{{Danish Football Hall of Fame}}\n{{Danish Football Player of the Year}}\n{{1986 FIFA World Cup Team of the Tournament}}\n{{FIFA World Cup Bronze Ball}}\n{{UEFA Intertoto Cup winning managers}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title=Denmark squads\n| bg = #e11b22\n| fg = White\n|list1=\n{{Denmark squad UEFA Euro 1984}}\n{{Denmark squad 1986 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Denmark squad UEFA Euro 1988}}\n}}\n{{Silkeborg IF managers}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Elkjaer, Preben}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:Danish footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:1. FC K\u00f6ln players]]\n[[Category:Belgian First Division A players]]\n[[Category:K.S.C. Lokeren Oost-Vlaanderen players]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:Hellas Verona F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Vejle Boldklub players]]\n[[Category:Denmark international footballers]]\n[[Category:Denmark under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:1986 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1984 players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1988 players]]\n[[Category:Danish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Germany]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Italy]]\n[[Category:Danish expatriate sportspeople in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Danish expatriate sportspeople in Germany]]\n[[Category:Danish expatriate sportspeople in Italy]]\n[[Category:Danish football managers]]\n[[Category:Silkeborg IF managers]]\n[[Category:Vanl\u00f8se IF players]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Danish Olympic athlete|Preben Larsen (athlete)}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n | name = Preben Elkj\u00e6r\n | image = Preben Elkj\u00e6r.jpg\n | image_size = 220px\n | caption = Elkj\u00e6r in June 2011 in [[Viborg, Denmark|Viborg]] (photo Lars Schmidt)\n | fullname = Preben Elkj\u00e6r\n | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1957|9|11|df=y}}\n | birth_place = [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]\n | height = {{height|m=1.82}}\n | position = [[Forward (association football)#Striker|Striker]]\n | youthyears1 = 1963\u20131973 | youthclubs1 = Frederiksberg BK\n | youthyears2 = 1973\u20131974 | youthclubs2 = [[Kj\u00f8benhavns Boldklub|KB]]\n | youthyears3 = 1974\u20131975 | youthclubs3 = Frederiksberg BK\n | years1 = 1976 | clubs1 = [[Vanl\u00f8se IF|Vanl\u00f8se]] | caps1 = 15 | goals1 = 7\n | years2 = 1977\u20131978 | clubs2 = [[1. FC K\u00f6ln]] | caps2 = 9 | goals2 = 1\n | years3 = 1978\u20131984 | clubs3 = [[K.S.C. Lokeren Oost-Vlaanderen|Lokeren]] | caps3 = 190 | goals3 = 98\n | years4 = 1984\u20131988 | clubs4 = [[Hellas Verona F.C.|Verona]] | caps4 = 91 | goals4 = 32\n | years5 = 1988\u20131990 | clubs5 = [[Vejle BK|Vejle]] | caps5 = 39 | goals5 = 12\n | totalcaps = 333 | totalgoals = 143\n | nationalyears1 = 1975\u20131976 | nationalteam1 = [[Denmark national under-19 football team|Denmark U19]] | nationalcaps1 = 11 | nationalgoals1 = 6\n | nationalyears2 = 1976\u20131979 | nationalteam2 = [[Denmark national under-21 football team|Denmark U21]] | nationalcaps2 = 9 | nationalgoals2 = 9\n | nationalyears3 = 1977\u20131988<ref>{{cite web | url =http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/elkjaer-intlg.html | title = Preben Elkj\u00e6r-Larsen - Century of International Appearances | accessdate = 11 July 2012 | publisher = The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation}}</ref> | nationalteam3 = [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] | nationalcaps3 = 69 | nationalgoals3 = 38\n| manageryears1 = 1995\u20131996 | managerclubs1 = [[Silkeborg IF|Silkeborg]]\n}}\n'''Preben Elkj\u00e6r''' ({{IPA-da|\u02c8\u025bl\u02cck\u025b\u02c0\u0250\u032f}}; born 11 September 1957) is a retired [[Denmark|Danish]] professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]].\n\nAmongst others, he played with [[Hellas Verona F.C.|Hellas Verona]] in [[Italy]], helping the club to the only major title of its history, the 1985 [[Serie A]]. Additionally, Elkj\u00e6r scored nearly 40 goals for the [[Denmark national football team|Danish national team]] in 11 years, being a leading figure for the Danish side under coach [[Sepp Piontek]] that played at the [[UEFA Euro 1984|Euro 1984]] and the [[1986 FIFA World Cup|1986 World Cup]] (a first-ever appearance), often hailed as the golden generation of [[Danish football]] by their countrymen. Elkj\u00e6r won the [[FIFA World Cup awards#Golden Ball|Bronze Ball]] award at the latter competition.  \n \nWidely regarded as one of the best forwards of the 1980s, Elkj\u00e6r finished second in the [[Ballon d'Or]] awards in 1985, having been placed third the previous year, and going on to finish fourth in [[1986 Ballon d'Or|1986]]. In [[Verona]] he is still remembered fondly, having earned the persisting nickname \"Il sindaco\" (the mayor) during his stint for the club. To this day, at least a few hundred voters in the city continue to write his name on their ballots at the mayoral elections.  Renowned for his goal-scoring abilities and persona, he also remains one of the most popular athletes in his native Denmark.\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Germany/Belgium===\nBorn September 11, 1957, in [[Copenhagen]], Elkj\u00e6r's career started with [[Vanl\u00f8se IF]] in 1976, where he stayed for just one season, playing 15 games and scoring seven goals. He then joined [[1. FC K\u00f6ln]] in [[Germany]], at the time one of [[Europe]]'s leading clubs. With the team, he won the 1978 [[DFB-Pokal|domestic Cup]] (his entire campaign consisted of nine minutes in the final, against [[Hertha BSC]]),<ref name=\"halloffame\">{{cite web | url = http://www.sportenshalloffame.dk/Default.aspx?ID=54 | title = Preben Elkj\u00e6r | publisher = SportensHallOfFame | language = Danish | accessdate = 17 April 2011}}</ref> but never got on with the manager or the harsh, disciplined atmosphere of a German dressing room,<ref>Lundberg (1988), p.91</ref> and eventually left. One falling out with the coach [[Hennes Weisweiler]] earned a legendary status in Denmark: Weisweiler approached Elkj\u00e6r and said that he had been informed that the player had spent the night at a nightclub in the company of a bottle of [[whiskey]] and a lady, and wanted to know if that was true. Elkj\u00e6r replied that it was a lie, in fact it was a bottle of [[vodka]] and ''two'' ladies.<ref name=\"Per H\u00f8yer Hansen: Det' H\u00f8yer\">Per H\u00f8yer Hansen: \"Det' H\u00f8yer\"</ref>\n\nIn February 1978, Elkj\u00e6r moved to [[K.S.C. Lokeren Oost-Vlaanderen]] in [[Belgium]] where he stayed for five years, the longest spell at any club during his entire career. There, he earned two nicknames: ''Chefen fra Lokeren'' (Lit: The Boss from Lokeren) and ''Den Gale Mand fra Lokeren'' (Lit: The Crazy Man from Lokeren),<ref name=\"Per H\u00f8yer Hansen: Det' H\u00f8yer\"/><ref name=\"DD\">{{cite news | author = Rob Smyth and Lars Eriksen | url = https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/oct/13/danish-dynamite-the-players | title = Danish Dynamite: The Players | work =[[The Guardian]] | date= 13 October 2009 | accessdate = 17 April 2011}}</ref> surpassing the 100-goal mark in official matches (98 in the [[Belgian First Division]] alone).\n\n===Verona===\nTwenty-seven-year-old Elkj\u00e6r signed for [[Hellas Verona F.C.]] in [[Italy]] in the summer of 1984 and, in [[1984\u201385 Serie A|his first season]] with the team, he played an instrumental role as it won the [[Serie A]] title, the ''[[List of Italian football champions|scudetto]]'', for the first time in its history; he aided to that conquest with a solo left-flank run against [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus FC]] (a 2\u20130 home win), where he lost his right boot, kept on running with the ball and ended up shooting home with his bootless right foot.<ref name=\"TheKnowledge\">{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/feb/08/theknowledge.sport | title = Socking it to the opposition | work = [[The Guardian]] | date = 8 February 2006 | accessdate = 17 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1984, Elkj\u00e6r finished third and in 1985 second in the [[Ballon d'Or|European Footballer of the Year]] awards, both times surpassed by [[Michel Platini]], who played for Juventus.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/europa-poy.html | title = European Footballer of the Year (\"Ballon d'Or\") | publisher= [[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] | accessdate = 17 April 2011}}</ref> During his four-year spell at Verona, he never scored ten league goals in a season, but never netted fewer than seven goals, for a total of 48 official ones.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.prebenelkjaer.com/carriera.php | title = Verona career | work = Official website | accessdate = 17 April 2011 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110715111748/http://www.prebenelkjaer.com/carriera.php | archivedate = 15 July 2011 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Return to Denmark/Retirement===\nIn 1988, Elkj\u00e6r made a comeback in Danish football with [[Vejle BK]].<ref name=\"halloffame\"/> He came to the club as the biggest star in the country, and attracted great crowds to the club's matches.<ref name=\"halloffame\"/> Aged already 31, he suffered a number of injuries while at Vejle,<ref name=\"halloffame\"/> and had a hard time living up to the high expectations of the crowds, eventually retiring two years later, having only appeared a total of 26 matches combined.\n\n==International career==\nWhile playing youth football for Frederiksberg Boldklub, Elkj\u00e6r made his debut for the Danish under-19 national team, in October 1975. He played a total 11 games and scored six goals for the under-19 national team, including three in three games at the 1975 [[UEFA European Under-19 Football Championship]].<ref name=\"Allekampe\">{{cite web | url = http://www.dbu.dk/landshold/landsholdsdatabasen/PlayerInfo/3708&allmatch=1#match | title = Preben Elkj\u00e6r \u2013 Alle hold (Alle kampe) | publisher =  DBU | language = Danish | accessdate = 17 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nElkj\u00e6r made his debut for the [[Denmark national under-21 football team|under-21s]] in June 1976,<ref name=\"Allekampe\"/> scoring nine times in as many games; this included three goals in the quarter-finals of the [[1978 UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship#Knockout stage|1978 European Under-21 Championship]] against [[Bulgaria national under-21 football team|Bulgaria]], though Denmark were eliminated on the [[away goals rule]].<ref name=\"Allekampe\"/>\n\nOn 22 June 1977, aged 19 years and 284 days, Elkj\u00e6r made his debut for the [[Denmark national football team|senior national team]], scoring both goals in a 2\u20131 win against [[Finland national football team|Finland]]. He played a prominent role in [[UEFA Euro 1984]], scoring two goals in four games,<ref name=\"Allekampe\"/> which helped pave the way for his move to Italian football.<ref>Lundberg (1988), p.136</ref> During the tournament, Denmark played attractive attacking football, but went out at the semi-final stage, losing to [[Spain national football team|Spain]] on [[Penalty shootout (association football)|penalties]].<ref name=\"Allekampe\"/> Elkj\u00e6r missed Denmark's last [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]] attempt, sending the ball high over the goal.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.dbu.dk/landshold/landsholdsdatabasen/LBaseMatchInfo.aspx?matchid=441 | title = Danmark \u2013 Spanien 1\u20131 | publisher = DBU | language = Danish | accessdate = 17 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nElkj\u00e6r also represented Denmark at the [[1986 FIFA World Cup]] as Denmark had qualified for [[FIFA World Cup|that competition]] for the first time, eventually progressing from the group stage as winners, only to be once again knocked out by Spain.<ref name=\"Allekampe\"/> During the tournament, he scored four goals, including a [[hat-trick]] against [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]],<ref name=\"Allekampe\"/> being named the most dynamic and powerful striker of the tournament,<ref name=\"FIFAp208\"/> and winning the [[FIFA World Cup awards#Golden Ball|Bronze Ball]] award as the third best player.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/fifa-gb86.html | title = FIFA Awards \u2013 World Cup 1986 \"Golden Ball\" | publisher = [[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] | accessdate = 17 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[UEFA Euro 1988|Euro 1988]] was Elkj\u00e6r's last tournament participation for him. On 14 June 1988, he played the last game for his country, aged 30 years and 277 days, as Denmark lost 0\u20132 to [[Germany national football team|West Germany]], finishing with three group stage defeats. In total, he played 69 international games, and scored 38 goals.<ref name=\"Allekampe\"/>\n\n==Playing style==\nElkj\u00e6r is regarded as one of Denmark's all-time greatest [[Forward (association football)|forwards]]. A notorious [[Tobacco smoking|smoker]],<ref name=\"DD\"/> his playing style was however not short of breath, being dominated by a rock-like determination.<ref name=\"DD\"/> He never seemed to give up on a lost ball \u2013 from time to time resulting in a goal.\n\nHis style was an unorthodox combination of physical confrontations<ref>Lundberg (1988), p.109</ref> and great [[dribbling]] abilities.<ref name=\"DD\"/> Described as \"powerful and dynamic\", Elkj\u00e6r could hardly be stopped when going on his own,<ref name=\"FIFAp208\">{{cite web | url = https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/afdeveloping/technicaldevp/50/09/00/fwc_mexico_1986_en_part4_279.pdf | title = FIFA World Cup \u2013 Mexico '86 \u2013 Official Report, p.208| publisher = [[FIFA]] | accessdate = 17 April 2011}}</ref> one of his trademarks. His aggression was matched by few,<ref name=\"halloffame\"/> and whenever he would receive the ball with his back to the goal he would immediately turn with the ball and attempt to head for goal.\n\nElkj\u00e6r's aggressive style of play was well combined with the calmness and vision of the younger [[Michael Laudrup]] when they played side by side on the national team,<ref name=\"FIFAp208\"/> and they were named the \"most effective\" attacking duo of the 1986 World Cup.<ref name=\"FIFAp208\"/>\n\n==Retirement==\nAfter his retirement from playing, Elkj\u00e6r took on the job as head coach of [[Silkeborg IF]] in the ''[[Danish Superliga]]'' in 1995.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.silkeborgif.com/historie.aspx | title = Historie | trans-title = History | publisher = Silkeborg | language = Danish | accessdate = 17 April 2011 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090131012258/http://silkeborgif.com/historie.aspx | archivedate = 31 January 2009 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> \n \nIn December 1996, he left the club to head TV sports channel ''TVS'', a newly formed corporation between national TV stations [[Danmarks Radio|DR]] and [[TV 2 (Denmark)|TV2]], the [[Danish Football Association]] and telecompany [[TDC A/S|Tele Danmark]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.danske-nyheder.dk/arkiv/1996.11.19.html#Elkj\u00e6r_TV-direkt\u00f8r | publisher = Danske-Nyheder.dk | title = Danish news on TVS from 19/11-1996 | language = Danish | accessdate = 17 April 2011}}</ref> The station was not a success, and was closed within a year of its opening.\n\nAdditionally, he worked as a [[UEFA Champions League]] [[Pundit (expert)|pundit]] at Danish [[Viasat|TV3+]], alongside [[Brian Laudrup]] and host Peter Gr\u00f8nborg.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.berlingske.dk/samfund/preben-elkjaer-om-nye-tv-tider-i-champions-league-nu-bliver-det-endnu-sjovere | publisher = Berlingske | title = Preben Elkj\u00e6r om nye TV-tider i Champions League: \u00bbNu bliver det endnu sjovere\u00ab | language = Danish | accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref>\n. In October 2019 he had an operation to remove a gallstone in Belgium.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bt.dk/fodbold/preben-elkjaer-hasteopereret-for-galdesten | publisher = BT | title = Preben Elkj\u00e6r hasteopereret for galdesten | language = Danish | accessdate = 18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Club===\n;[[1. FC K\u00f6ln]]\n*[[Bundesliga]]: [[1977\u201378 Bundesliga|1977\u201378]]\n*[[DFB-Pokal]]: [[1976\u201377 DFB-Pokal|1976\u201377]], [[1977\u201378 DFB-Pokal|1977\u201378]]\n\n;[[Hellas Verona F.C.|Verona F.C.]]\n*[[Serie A]]: [[1984\u201385 Serie A|1984\u201385]]\n\n===Individual===\n*[[Danish Football Player of the Year|Danish Player of the Year]]: 1984\n*[[Ballon d'Or (1956\u20132009)|Ballon d'Or]] \u2013 Third Place: 1984<ref>{{citeweb|url= http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/europa-poy84.html|title=European Footballer of the Year (\"Ballon d'Or\") 1984|work=RSSSF|accessdate=14 April 2015 }}</ref>\n*[[Ballon d'Or (1956\u20132009)|Ballon d'Or]] \u2013 Runner-up: 1985<ref>{{citeweb|url= http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/europa-poy85.html|title=European Footballer of the Year (\"Ballon d'Or\") 1985|work=RSSSF|accessdate=14 April 2015 }}</ref>\n*[[Onze d'Or|Onze de Bronze]] : [[Onze d'Or|1984]]\n*[[Onze d'Or|Onze d'Argent]] : [[Onze d'Or|1985]]\n*[[FIFA World Cup awards#Golden Ball|FIFA World Cup Bronze Ball]]: 1986\n*[[FIFA World Cup awards#All-Star Team|FIFA World Cup All-Star Team]]: 1986\n*[[Denmark national football team#Hall of Fame|Danish Football Hall of Fame]]\n*[[World Soccer Magazine|World Soccer The Greatest Players of the 20th century]]: The 100 Greatest Footballers of All Time<ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/best-x-players-of-y.html#ws100 World Soccer: The 100 Greatest Footballers of All Time] Retrieved 30 December 2015</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n===Footnotes===\n*{{cite book |title=Dansk Fodbold |last=Lundberg |first=Knud |authorlink= Knud Lundberg|volume=3. Gennembrudet til verdensklasse |coauthors= |year=1988 |publisher=Rhodos |location=Copenhagen |isbn=87-7245-260-9 |page= |pages= |url= |accessdate=}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Preben Elkj\u00e6r}}\n* [http://www.dbu.dk/landshold/landsholdsdatabasen/PlayerInfo/3708 National team data] {{in lang|da}}\n* [http://www.vejle-boldklub.dk/index.php?gammel_spillere=6406 Vejle Boldklub profile] {{in lang|da}}\n* {{Fussballdaten|elkjaerlarsenpreben|Preben Elkj\u00e6r Larsen}}\n* {{NFT player|pid=19458}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.prebenelkjaer.com/}}\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title=Awards\n|bg=Gold\n|bordercolor=Black\n|fg=Black\n|list1=\n{{Danish Football Hall of Fame}}\n{{Danish Football Player of the Year}}\n{{1986 FIFA World Cup Team of the Tournament}}\n{{FIFA World Cup Bronze Ball}}\n{{UEFA Intertoto Cup winning managers}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title=Denmark squads\n| bg = #e11b22\n| fg = White\n|list1=\n{{Denmark squad UEFA Euro 1984}}\n{{Denmark squad 1986 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Denmark squad UEFA Euro 1988}}\n}}\n{{Silkeborg IF managers}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Elkjaer, Preben}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:Danish footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:1. FC K\u00f6ln players]]\n[[Category:Belgian First Division A players]]\n[[Category:K.S.C. Lokeren Oost-Vlaanderen players]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:Hellas Verona F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Vejle Boldklub players]]\n[[Category:Denmark international footballers]]\n[[Category:Denmark under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:1986 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1984 players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1988 players]]\n[[Category:Danish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Germany]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Italy]]\n[[Category:Danish expatriate sportspeople in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Danish expatriate sportspeople in Germany]]\n[[Category:Danish expatriate sportspeople in Italy]]\n[[Category:Danish football managers]]\n[[Category:Silkeborg IF managers]]\n[[Category:Vanl\u00f8se IF players]]\n", "name_user": "Nardog", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:fixingDanish IPA", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Preben_Elkj%C3%A6r"}
